According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While offloading at consignee location, Terminal Warehouse, a leak occurred.  Apparently the hose was not secured inside the facility, prior to commencement of offload, which resulted in the release of approximately 55 gallons of free product.  The free product released to the concrete surface inside the facility.  All product was contained inside facility, there was no environmental impact, no soils or waters of the state were affected.  Terminal Warehouse personnel performed the cleanup with the application of floor dry to the free liquid, which was recovered, and placed into recovery drums, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: In order to prevent recurrence of the incident or similar incidents, Slay Transportation Co., Inc. drivers are required to attend safety meetings.  Safety meetings address such issues as handling spills, driving hazards, and job specific training.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. drivers are required to attend DOT job specific training classes.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. addresses safety issues in their driver’s newsletter.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safety guidelines to all employees.

column168: As soon as driver noticed product on side of the cargo tank, he pulled over.  The front washout cap had come off the cargo tank.  We called out HMHTTC to respond to the incident cleanup.  The site was secured and no product got in any waterways.  One lane of traffic remained open.  Cleanup was completed by approximately 2230.  The missing washout cap was found on the roadway but it was replaced with a new one to ensure there was a tight seal.
column169: The shipper had secured the washout caps but the driver failed to follow proper procedure by checking them to make sure they were secure.  It appears that the front one may have been cross-threaded and the surge from going downhill may have been enough to pop it off.  Because of the incident, the driver was scheduled to meet with a trainer for performance enhancement training stressing pre-trip procedures.  That was completed on 2/3/2010.

column168: On 02/02/10 at 04:15 hrs., personnel in the Big 4 yard in Russell, KY discovered ETCX 22042, a loaded tank car of Diethyl Ether, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated, the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2010-02-02-00028), TOBIN.HOLZHUTER@LYONDELL.COM, and the local 911 was notified. SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene to inspect and secure the car. McCulley Eastham and Associates, was dispatched to the scene to perform air monitoring. SPSI personnel discovered old packing material between the ball valve and the ball valve seat which allowed product release beyond the ball valve. The old packing material was removed from the ball valve, the plug was reinstalled, and the leak stopped. An FRA movement approval was requested by the shipper and granted to move the car back to Tuscola, IL (Number FRA-10020072).    This incident did require several switching moves in the yard to gain access to the car by contractors.            A QA-7.1 Nonconformance Report will be submitted for this incident.    Cause Code:  296  NARRI: 2 (5 +5+0) X (2+0) = 40

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  The shipments would ultimately be reloaded on trailers destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  When on the dock, the cardboard outer portion of the flex bin was noticed to be stained.  A response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, placed the container on a spill pan and re-containerized the shipment, along with the cleanup materials.  The shipment was then loaded on a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: AT the time the shipment was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed.  It was determined that the polyethylene liner in the IBC was found to have a small split in it, causing the material to leak out and rest against the outer wall of the flex bin-staining it.  No material escaped onto the trailer or dock floor. The shipper was advised of the incident and was advised to ensure that care be taken when loading material to avoid inadvertanlty cutting or tearing an inner lining.

column168: February 15, 2010: At approximately 1:00PM, Conrail crew ME5 was performing normal switching operations in Conrail's Metuchen (NJ) Yard, and noted a strong pungent odor from an unknown source, similar to what they've experienced at Exxon-Mobil's Metuchen (NJ) facility when they switch that plant.  Cars destined for Exxon-Mobil were located on Track #10 in the yard. This is the serving yard for that customer.    After inspecting numerous cars in the yard, with Conrail Trainmaster H. Nagel, Exxon-Mobil (consignee) representative R. Young, and 2 representatives of REACT (environmental and emergency response contractor for Conrail), CR's Risk Manager A. Richter noted tank car TILX 191063, load Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Organic, NOS (Isopentanoic Acid), Class 8, UN 3265, PG III, very slight seeping in and around the bottom outlet valve operating handle's stem packing.      Attempts to secure the packing by tightening the 2-nut arrangement on the packing gland proved unsuccessful.   As the release was merely weeping/seeping and no evidence was noted on the ground under the valve, it was decided to wrap the packing nut with chemical absorbent pads and secure them to the area.  Arrangements were made to switch the car into the plant at the next available switch (following day, Tuesday, February 16), which was accomplished.

column168: Shipper: CIS Chimie Tech Services AWB# 2160394515On 02/08/2010 at 0900, a shipment was discovered leaking at the DHL Service Center located at 420 E Street, Boston MA 02127. The shipment was bagged, the leak was absorbed with Speedy-Dri and the package was moved to the Hazardous Materials Sort Cage. BOS Station personnel contacted shipper for a copy of the MSDS.On 02/09/2010 at 1220, Mike Shields with the BOS Service Center contacted the DHL Dangerous Goods Hotline to report the shipment, once the MSDS arrived from shipper and package was discovered to contain Class 8, UN3264. I am awaiting a callback to make arrangements for FAA investigation of this shipment. Tracking indicates initial transportation by air.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop for the purpose of consolidating less than truck-load quantities of hazardous waste onto a single vehicle for continued transportation.  During the container transfer operation, the fork-lift operator misjudged the clearance between the bottom of the container and the dock plate when loading the container in question into an alternative van trailer.  The bottom chime of the container struck the dock plate causing a small crack to develop on the drum. The fork-lift operator set the rum down and notified an in house response team.  Upon arrival, the team, wearing appropriate personnel protective equipment, placed the damaged container into a suitable salvage drum.  A suitable absorbent material was used to absorb all free liquid released and this, along with all clean-up debris was collected and placed into the salvage drum.  At the conclusion of the response activities, the container was secured and placed onto the van trailer for continued transportation to the intended waste management facility.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the fork-lift operator was cautioned about his apparent inattention to his surroundings as this was a preventable incident.  Furthermore, the operator will be required to attend a refresher training class on the operation of fork-lift equipment.  IN addition, the employee has been advised that future occurrences will subject him to disciplinary actions up to and including termination of employment.

column168: Six ctns containing 2 gallon cans of paint each, were top loaded on a 10 foot long pallet under load decks. Four of the ctns were loaded on the side in clear view and two were loaded on top of a pallet on a third shipment. The last two were hidden and could not be seen by the unloader. When the unloader pulled the pallet out from under the load racks, onto the dock, the two hidden ctns fell off the pallet onto the cement. The lid on one of the gallon cans dented and popped open slightly, releasing the paint into the overpack ctn and onto the floor. The leaking ctn was quickly placed into a plastic bag and loaded into a plastic 5 gallon pail. The small spill on the floor was cleaned up with paper towels and also placed into the 5 gallon pail.

column168: Linde driver was northbound on I-75 near Niota, TN and was overtaken by a car in the left lane. As the car passed it started to hydroplane and slide toward the Linde truck. The driver started braking and moved to the shoulder of the interstate to avoid the vehicle. The passenger car kept coming to the right towards the Linde truck and forced the Linde vehicle onto the shoulder causing the right wheels to drop off the edge and into the rain soaked mud on the soft shoulder. The truck and trailer started to slide towards small embankment , overturning and coming to rest off the highway.  The driver suffered a fractured collarbone.    The cargo tank suffered damage to the outer and innner vessel.  There was no release of product due to damage.  The product was transfered to another cargo tank prior to uprighting.

column168: 8, 5-gallon metal drums were stacked on top of 8, 5 gallon drums shrink-wrapped onto one wooden pallet.  This palle twas placed into a trailer with additional freight placed on top of the pallet of paint, the weight on top of the pallet of paint caused crushing to one of the 5 gallon drums.  The result being the leaking of paint onto the drum underneath and the wooden pallet containing all drums.
column169: Freight should not be placed on top of any pallets/drums/containers of paint in the future.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: Amerochem short truck #2010 was traveling on Hwy 403 outside the town of Faison,NC at 07:40 in light rain. The driver met another truck and moved over such that the right rear wheels went of the road surface onto a very soft narrow shoulder. The driver attempted to correct, lost control, and the truck rolled over several times. The Hypochlorite IBC was ejected from the damaged truck body and was found on its side with the top cracked and a third of the contents remaining. It could not be determined if the damage resulted from contact with the truck body or direct failure from force of the contents on the top. The ditch was excavated and approximately 4000 lbs of affected soil were removed and the ditch restored.  The driver was unconscious but recovered and later released from the hospital.Chlorine cylinders also on the truck did not release but caused responders to evacuate approximatly 20 people.

On 02/05/10 at 03:37 hrs., employees in the Big 4 yard in Russell, KY were performing switching operations when one of the employees detected an odor of  bleach.  PPGX 86330, a residue tank car of chlorine, was discovered leaking from under the protective housing. The employees were removed from the area and the car was left on the switch lead. The shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2010-02-05-00013) contact: Patrick Huth  - 502-732-4411, Ext. 296  CSX HazMat manager, Jim Briski, responded with McCulley Eastham + Associates and  Weavertown Environmental. The shipper's intact security seal was removed from the protective housing and an inspection determined the B end liquid line was loose  to  turn and the B end liquid line plug was loose 2- turns. The B end liquid line and plug were tightened and the leak stopped. The car was switched to an isolated lead where SPSI, an emergency response contractor for PPG Industries performed an additional inspection of the tank car. No leaks were found therefore the car was released for transport.   This incident did require a special switch move to isolate the car.   A QA-7.1 Non conformance Report will not be required for this incident.    Cause Code: 119  NARRI:  5 (4+10+1) X (2+0) = 150

column168: On 02/05/10 at 12:50 hrs., a car department inspector at the rail yard in Niagara Falls, NY, discovered UTLX 204603, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking product from the top of the car during switching operations.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Granite Falls Energy, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2010-02-05-00112). CSXT Hazmat Manager, Michael Bethge, responded to the scene and found the PRD valve (reclosing - 165 Lb) to be broken, being able to lift the closure cap. The owner of the tank car, UTC, was notified and retained Rescar to replace the PRD. The FRA issued a movement approval for the tank car to be emptied of product and then sent to a UTC shop for a leakage test and PRD valve inspection.    Cause Code:418  NARRI: 2(5+3+0) X (2+0) = 32

On 02/06/10 at 02:56 hrs., personnel in the Queensgate yard in Cincinnati, OH discovered TILX 301709, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquids N.O.S., leaking vapors from under the protective housing. The car was isolated and the shipper, NOVA Chemical, was notified.  Eagle/SWS, a CSX emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the B end liquid valve was open  to  turn and the B end liquid valve plug was loose 2 and  turns. Eagle/SWS personnel closed the valve, tightened the plug and the leak stopped. Corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Kevin J. DeAngelis, 419-490-4186 and the car was released for transportation. This incident did require a special switch move.         A 7.1 is not required with this incident.   Cause Code: 119  NARRI:   5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100

A California PUC rail safety inspector inspecting an inbound BNSF train in the railyard reported entrained GETX 3108 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from its top valve housing area. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders were notified and immediately inspected GETX 3108. The responders reported intact valve housing seal numbered 168767 was removed for valve inspection. The two inch liquid line valve stem was observed as the leak source. The valve handle was in the closed position, but it was loose on the valve stem. Under the handle, the valve stem packing retainer nut was found to be finger loose which was the cause of the product leak. Once the valve stem packing retainer nut was tool tightened, the product leak ceased. The valve handle was reapplied and properly tool tightened on the valve stem. The valve housing was resealed with seal BNSF 06157912. Spillage evaporated. Also, GETX 3108 had four UN1170 placards applied and these were removed since they didn't match the commodity billing received from the shipper. These were replaced by the proper UN3065 placards. No further product release was reported from GETX 3108 during subsequent movements in the railyard.  The side specification stencil on GETX 3108 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2000 and next due in 2010.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

On 02/17/10 at 11:42 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Boyles Yard in Birmingham, AL discovered UTLX 210448, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, NOS, leaking from the top of the car. The car was left in the track and the shipper was notified of the incident via CHEMTREC (Report #2010-20-17-000110). CSXT emergency response contractor, SWS, was dispatched to the scene and found the sample line valve was open and the plug was not in the valve. Randy Kline of Cargill, Inc, phone #952-742-6899, was notified of the incident and the finding. SWS personnel closed the valve, replaced the plug and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switch move.   A 7.1 Nonconformance Report will not be required.  Cause Code:  145  NARRI: 5 (3+3+0) x (2+0) = 60

On 02/17/10 at 22:01 hrs., personnel in the CSXT rail yard in Riverdale, IL discovered tank car, UTLX 12333, a load of Phosphoric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, PCS Sales, Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2010-02-17-00226). Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the manway cover gasket was brittle and cracked.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to Mr. Virgil Fowler with PCS Sales, 706-564-8423. Eagle/SWS personnel installed a new Teflon manway cover gasket and decontaminated the side of the car.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.  Cause Code: 209  NARRI: 5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) =  80

On 02/18/10 at 01:56 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Boyle Yard in Birmingham, AL derailed 12 rail cars, including 8 residue hazardous material cars. During re-railing operations, CSXT personnel discovered MWTX 112708, a residue tank car of Alcohols, NOS, leaking from the bottom outlet. CSXT emergency response contractor, SWS, found the bottom outlet valve had packing nuts that were knocked loose during the derailment.  The shipper, Biourja Trading LLC, was notified of the incident via CHEMTREC (Report# 2010-02-18-00014). SWS personnel tightened the packing nuts and the leak stopped. The tank car was loaded on carrying equipment and sent home for repairs.     No switch move required.  No 7.1 will be required.      Cause Code:  ATARI:

February 15, 2010: At approximately 1:00PM, Conrail crew ME5 was performing normal switching operations in Conrail's Metuchen (NJ) Yard, and noted a strong pungent odor from an unknown source, similar to what they've experienced at Exxon-Mobil's Metuchen (NJ) facility when they switch that plant.  Cars destined for Exxon-Mobil were located on Track #10 in the yard. This is the serving yard for that customer.    After inspecting numerous cars in the yard, with Conrail Trainmaster H. Nagel, Exxon-Mobil (consignee) representative R. Young, and 2 representatives of REACT (environmental and emergency response contractor for Conrail), CR's Risk Manager A. Richter noted tank car ACFX 71549, load Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Organic, NOS (Isopentanoic Acid), Class 8, UN 3265, PG III, with a wet 2" closure plug for the bottom outlet auxiliary valve, due the auxiliary valve being partially open.  The closure plug was noted tool tight but wrench applied and made as tool tight as possible at the time of finding.  Valve closed, plug wiped with chemical absorbent pad and watched for 15 minutes, with no further release noted.      Car to be ordered in by original consignee when needed at the plant.  No further exceptions noted.

column168: During transit a 55 gallon drum containing Corrosive Liquid Basic Inorganic N.O.S. fell through a deteriorated wooden skid. When the material was declared safe to clean up, the spilled product was absorbed with oil dry and placed in a salvage container along with the damaged drum and all clean-up materials.

column168: On February 3rd, 2010 during the inspection of cargo due to the freight shifted on transit, the carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed that the container SMLU831861 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo. The reason for the cargo shifting during transport was the lack of blocking and bracing as required by 49 CFR part 176. The container was immediately placed on HOLD status and the shipper was advised of the findings. The shipper was asked to properly block and brace the cargo, and to provide the properly documentation. On February 10TH the cargo was properly declared, marked, blocked braced and released for transport.

column168: Driver arrives at the customer site.  Both he and the customer agree that the tank has enough room to hold all the product.  The tank we were unloading in to was inside the building and his truck/trailer were outside.  The driver had 4622 gallons to unload.  The customers tank has a 5000 gallon capacity with 1 foot currently in the tank and the tank is 10 feet high.  This should have eqauted to 500 gallons for a starting amount in the tank.  The driver admits he did not physically calculate how much capacity the tank could hold.  Had he done this it would have been clear that the tank could not hold the entire contents of our trailer but should not have eqauted to the 1237 gallons that actually spilled.  It should have been more like 122 gallons plus some extra because of the force of air pressure.      The driver started to offload and checked the customers tank 3 times during the unload.  The third time the customers tank level reflected 4500 gallons.  He quickly went back to the truck and was waiting for the hoses to go empty (at this time he had 25 psi on the trailer and valves open all the way) but then instead he felt a bunch of back pressure and immediately shut down.  He went in to the building and product was coming out of a drain hose (attached to the top of the tank) which empties into a containment area. We later learned that the customer said the actual starting tank level was 692 gallons instead of 500 which helps identify where some additional spillage came from.  Should have been 314-350 gallons that spilled now.  The plant did have an adjoined tank for this product and it was empty but the eqaulizer valve was not open.  Their overflow warning system failed to operate until 1.5 hours afterwards.  We checked with the shipper and the scale tickets and the weights all appear to be in the amount requested.  When the driver checked for residual product he still had 62 gallons left in his trailer.  The customer said they verified the capacity on the tank is accurate.  We do know that the site glass was replaced on the tank recently.  The only logical conclusion we could come to is that the site glass was vapor locked and not reflecting accurately (ex - 1 foot was actually 2 feet).  I state this is the reason as the fill line was connected to the tank at the bottom.  Even if it was just high air pressure going into the tank when it was at the overflow level (which the overflow drain line was also connected at the very top) it would not have caused this significant of an overflow.  Typically there will be a 20 gallon or less spill.       Reason Summations:  1. Driver did not do any calculations prior to delivery - did not back down pressure or product flow at the end of his delivery like we train our drivers to do.    2. Customer overflow alarm did not work correctly  3. Presumably a site gauge issue on the customer tank
column169: 1. Driver was brought in for Performance Enhancement Training to review the key area's he could have prevented this incident  *Verify capacities and amounts prior to unloading  *If the tank is not visible request someone from the plant to monitor the tank and communicate via walkie talkie's  *Reduce air pressure and cut back valve flow    2. Customer corrections:  *fix the overflow alarm system  *monitor site glass on next delivery - currently they do not believe this was an issue.    *open adjoining fill line to secondary tank to prevent overflow

column168: SHIPPER: AMANA CARE SARL/ AWB# 7992738736                                              On 02/22/2010 at 1051, CVG Licensed Custom Broker, Mike Horn, contacted the DHL Dangerous Goods Hotline in regard to a possible disposal of small metal aerosol cans in an FDA held shipment sitting in the Customs Area of DHL Express, 236 Wendell H. Ford Blvd, Erlanger, KY 41018.  I met Mike Horn at the Customs entrance and he escorted me to the shipment.  Inside the package, I discovered 10 boxes, each containing 3 metal cans of Amana Care Pilatory.  Also inside the package were 50 plastic bottles of Amana Care Extra Borojo Tablets and 30 Amana Care Brochures.  Although the metal cans are not marked as "contents under pressure," they do have the appearance of an aerosol.  With permission from Customs, I returned to the shipment today (02/23/2010) for further investigation and pictures.  After my investigation, I packed the shipment back into its original outer packaging and left it in the Customs Area where it is still "on hold" per the FDA.  The shipment did not leak and there was no detectable odor.  Tracking indicates initial transportation by air.

Material was shipped to Veolia as Non DOT Regulated Material (computer and electrical equipment) in a one cubic yard container (IBC). Shipment arrived at Veolia on February 2, 2010. Upon inspection and receiving, it was noted that the shipment also contained PCB light ballasts and small capacitors (non TSCA). The container was held as a potential rejection and an investigation was performed. After the customers investigation the customer determined the PCB ballasts were TSCA regulated. Veolia received the material on 2/17/2009.     On February 1, 2009 the above referenced waste was transported by Veolia ES Technical Solutions from the Ashland, Carson, CA facility on a non-hazardous waste-shipping document (155384RLF). At the time of the shipment it was not known that the shipping container also contained TSCA regulated light ballasts along with the computer and electronic scrap. The error was not caught prior to the material arriving at our facility. The ballasts were not discovered until the container was opened for routine inspection performed in our receiving department.

Our anhydrous ammonia TW arrived on site at 8:10am, KMG operator made contact with the our driver and let him know it was safe to start hooking up the hose while operator went inside to grab his coat. When KMG operator returned outside he noticed a white cloud of anhydrous ammonia at the TW and he and the driver went upwind.    8:10 am- Our driver opened  the “snappy joe” valve, and took off the end cap on the 2” liquid hose and layed the hose on the ground on the south side of the wagon so the valve handle was vertical. Our driver then walked around to the north side of the TW and began pulling the hose underneath the trailer to perform his hook up. When he began pulling, the hose twisted and the valve handle contacted the ground causing it to open ¼ turn to 1/8 turn. He ran around the south side of the trailer to the “snappy joe” valve but saw he could not get there because of the leaking ammonia. He then went to the west side (back of the trailer) to activate the emergency shut off valve. The ammonia did not stop at this point. The KMG operator met with the driver at this time and the KMG operator called his supervisor. The fire alarm was pulled and employees were alerted to begin to shelter in place. A group of emergency responders went around to the west side of the building (upwind) and met with the driver and KMG operator to get more information. The KMG responders pulled the SCBA’s and PPE from the Truck wash emergency response box and proceeded to the southwest corner of the building. Two responders went to get the draeger tube kits and began to check the atmosphere at the east fence line. A  KMG responder got a pitchfork to try and position the hose to point downwind. Using chemical gloves and respirator the KMG responder’s intention was to position the hose to the east so that the “snappy joe” valve could be shut off (in the middle of the TW). When moving the unloading hose on the south side of the truck the wind was strong enough to keep the vapors away from the immediate area and the KMG responder. The KMG responder was able to safely shut the manual globe valve at the end of the liquid hose. After the valve was shut off we let the anhydrous on the ground evaporate (about 5 minutes). Shelter in place employees were given the okay to return to work at 8:42 a.m.    After the incident, our driver had the TW weighed at Transit Mix and returned to Pueblo plant, where supervisors determined it was safe to offload the wagon and not reject it. The weight tickets had a 580lb difference in the tare weight, which was attributed by Airgas to diesel fuel and possibly scale difference. The tank wagon was offloaded without further issues.

column168: Notified at 1247 hrs by DTS that tank car CGTX 30419 was leaking from the dome area. Arrived on scene at 1320 hrs. Climbed on rail car and observed small quantity of fluid leaking from the threads around the 2" liquid line valve. Notified M&M Protection at 1318 hrs, they arrived on scene at 1356 hrs. Further investigation revealed that the installer of the valve did not use and thread sealant (thread locker) when installing the valve. This allowed product to leak out around the threads. M&M Protection removed the valve, cleaned the threads, added thread sealant and re-applied the valve. M&M cleared the scene at 1445 hrs.  PTRA personnel used absorbent pads to soak up the product on the side and top of the car. No product was observed on the ground. M&M disposed of the pads. Estimate less than one gallon of product released. The tank car had 12" outage as measured from the manway.

column168: Tractor trailer #Q3069 was involved in a single vehicle roll-over accident into a water-filled ditch.     Cleanup Operations: ACT as the cleanup management company for Quality Carriers, contracted with USES to respond and assess the site.  Upon arrival the response team advised that the tanker was upside down in a ditch with an estimated 2000 gallons of product released.  The tank was drilled and the remaining product was offloaded into another tanker provided by Quality Carriers.  The liquid in the ditch had a pH of 1.  The liquid was neutralized with soda ash, caustic and lime.  Once neutralized the liquid was pumped out and stored off site in tanks for disposal.  An excavation of contaminated soil is planned for Wednesday, February 17, 2010 to remove all contaminated soil.  The excavation area measures approximately 350-feet long by 10 feet wide.     All waste will disposed of at Clean Harbors in White Castle, Louisiana.    An additional work plan for sampling and final cleanup was required by LA-DEQ to meet LA-RECAP requirments.    WORK PLAN    The first part of the Work Plan will consist soil sample collection, field analyses of soil samples for pH, and laboratory analysis of soil samples     Soil Assessment Activities     Soil sample collection and decontamination procedures will be performed using standard protocols approved by LDEQ according to the RECAP Appendix B Site Investigation Requirements, engineering practices approved by the American Society of Testing Materials (ASTM), written procedures contained in A•C•T’s Corporate Quality Assurance Plan, and other scientific and engineering practices in conformance with standards for the industry.    Soil sample collection will be performed in the previously excavated area.  We estimate a total of 27 soil samples will be collected for laboratory analyses.  Five (5) on each side of the excavation and one (1) at each end.  Samples will be collected from the ground surface around the perimeter of the excavation and from approximately one (1) foot below the edge of the excavation.  At least three (3) background samples will also be collected from nearby locations, and concentrations of pH and sulfides will be compared to spill location concentrations.         Soil samples for laboratory analyses will be collected with a properly decontaminated stainless steel hand auger or other appropriate equipment.  The samples will be collected following LDEQ/RECAP soil sample collection and field decontamination guidance.  Equipment (rinsate) blanks and field duplicate (replicate) samples will be collected.  No trip blank will be collected since volatile organic compound analyses will not be performed.    Field pH analyses will be conducted on the collected soil samples.  Soil sample collection and analyses will generally follow the method described in Procedures for Collecting Soil Samples and Methods of Analysis for Soil Survey published by the United States Department of Agriculture – Soil Conservation

column168: The driver was loading compartment 1 (capacity of 3000 gal)and compartment 3 (capacity 2000 gal) with fuel.  He mixed up the compartment capacities and overfilled compartment 3.   The cargo tank overflow protection system was working properly and did shut down but because the driver was set to pull more product than would fit in the compartment, the flow rate had not slowed down yet and overfilled before it shut down.  If driver had punched in the correct amount to put in that compartment, the flow rate would have been going slower when it got closer to the top and would have shut down before overflowing.  This was deemed human error on the drivers part. The spill went into a containment area.
column169: The driver went through performance enhancement and committment training, and also received additional training on the rack procedures.  We are incorporating the learnings from this incident into our training program for all fuel hauling drivers.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTV PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: Transporter was attempting to load denatured alcohol at Corn Plus in Winnebago, MN to be delivered to Marathon Petroleum in St Paul Park, MN. The driver connected the bottom loading arm to compartment #4, holds 2700 gallons, and programmed the meter to load 3500 galons. The overfill protection failed to stop the loading and the compartment overfilled. Product went into the vapor recovery line, traveled into other compartments through the vapor recovery rail, and was forced out the dome lid from being overfilled. About 103 gallons went on the ground in the containment area, no environmental impact was experienced. There is an ongoing investigation but it was found that there is a switch at the load rack which switches the overfill protection between the transports and railcars. If the switch is on railcar it still allowed the transport to load without protection. This was human error to not have the switch in the correct position but also don't know if it was a lack of procedures of training.

On Friday February 26th at approximately 12:45 pm while in the process of loading the fourth compartment of a Keystone Petroleum trailer with ethanol from railcar TILX 198211, the loader heard a loud sound as the railcar suddenly imploded. The loader immediately pressed the emergency stop button on the pump and radioed for help, then proceeded to attempt to close the railcar product valve. As the manager and several responders arrived on the scene it was observed that the bottom product valve would not completely close due to the damage and was still leaking from around the tank car adapter. The team proceeded to take a pipe wrench and straighten the valve stow cradle and was then able to completely close the valve and stop the leak. There was approximately two gallons of ethanol contained within the track pan. The team immediately secured the area and made all required notifications. Upon initial investigation of the incident it was confirmed that the vapor recovery system was properly connected and that valves were properly opened and all verifications had been properly conducted. The cause of the incident is currently under investigation.
column169: During the course of the incident investigation, critical parts of the load setup were allowed to leave the facility prior to completion of the investigation. Recommend that all: Equipment, paperwork, records, railcars, trailers and any other parts of the load setup remain onsite until the investigation is completed, regardless of which entity is conducting the investigation.

column168: (A)During a railcar inspection in the railyard by a FRA Railroad Safety Inspector, ADMX 29662 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was noted with an audible 'vapor hiss' and residue product odor emanating from its manway closure. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder that was with the Railroad Safety Inspector tool tightened 1 of 6 manway securement bolt nuts that was found less than tool tight. Afterwards, a faint 'vapor hiss' persisted. BNSF contract responders were called to assist in the elimination of the 'vapor hiss' from ADMX 29662. The responders opened the manway lid and reported finding the manway gasket in good condition but out of position which most likely prevented a good manway closure seal. Responder's correctly positioned the manway gasket, closing the manway lid and properly tool tightening all manway securement bolt nuts. Upon completion of this securement adjustment, no further 'vapor hiss' was evident. This response was concluded by 1520 hrs. CST, 2/18/2010. (B)During a railcar inspection in the railyard by a FRA Railroad Safety Inspector, ADMX 29707 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was noted with an audible 'vapor hiss' and residue product odor emanating from a capped fitting atop its manway cover. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder that was with the Railroad Safety Inspector inspected the capped fitting atop what appeared to be a sample line pipe riser and it was tool tight. Later, BNSF contract responders on site loosened the manway securement bolts to depressurized ADMX 29707. The capped fitting was found to be cross threaded atop the pipe riser. Also, the pipe riser was cross-threaded at the manway orifice. The responders opened the manway lid and reported finding no manway gasket. The responders procured a proper fitting pipe riser with closure cap and installed it atop the manway lid. Teflon packing was inserted into the manway lid gasket track. The manway cover was closed and properly tool tightened. Afterwards, no residue product odor or 'vapor hiss' was evident. ADMX 29707 was directed back to the car owner/lessee for their inspection and furtherance. This response was concluded by 1800 hrs. CST, 2/18/2010.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Our bulk driver was headed west on MLK Drive in the far right lane when a passenger vehicle flagged his attention.The driver noticed product splashes on the side of the tanker and pulled over. The driver contacted dispatch immediately. Local fire and police responded to the scene. A 3" vacuum cap was discovered to have fallen off of the tanker approximately 1,000 yards east of the vehicle.EMCO's fire responders collected all paperwork, including MSDS, identifying the material in the tanker, assessed the situation, and placed absorbent materials on the ground where product splashing occurred. With the permission ofthe local fire and state police authorities EMCO's HazMat Team cleaned up all materials from the roadway and replaced the damaged cap at the scene.A sewer cover at the west end of the vehicle was removed by North Chicago Fire Dept. and air monitored, indicating the presence of <1 PPM toluene. EMCO HazMat Team placed a boom in the hole. Local IEPA agent did not believe there was any impact to the local storm sewer. To ensure the collection of any potential foreign matter, EMCO placed a boom downstream for a week period. The boom was then removed and disposed of accordingly.The estimated quantity of release was approximately 5 gallons. No reportable quantities of materials were exceeded, and there were no injuries.
column169: EMCO plans to take the following preventative measures to prevent future occurrence of incidents of this nature as follows:1. All cargo tankers in our fleet were be inspected for loose 3" vacuum caps.2. All employees associated with loading, unloading, cleaning, and transporting tankers, including spotters, were notified and retrained on the importance of assuring all caps are securely closed prior to transport.

A BNSF train operating on single main track derailed 24 railcars after transversing a turnout switch.  Amongst the derailed railcars was FTLX 311731 (AAR C113 three compartment covered hopper) that derailed on its side. The ground impact caused the top hatchways on FTLX 311731 to jar open with subsequent release of its lading onto the ground. The top hatchways were closed by BNSF responders and FTLX 311731 was covered with tarps. Ground spillage was vacuumed and placed in vacuum boxes for appropriate disposal. The remaining lading in FTLX 311731 was transferred into another suitable covered hopper and forwarded to the original consignee. FTLX 311731 deemed destroyed, was cleaned and scheduled for dismantling.    A BNSF train operating on single main track derailed 24 railcars after transversing a turnout switch.  Amongst the derailed railcars was SRIX 80097 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) that derailed leaning and sustained a puncture at the manway nozzle (approximately 8 inches in diameter and approximately one foot above the nozzle base). Product escaped from this manway nozzle breach until the internal product level was below the breach hole in the nozzle. Spillage on the ground solidified and was excavated. Recovered ground spillage and the remaining product in SRIX 80097 that was extracted were placed into roll-off boxes and transported off-site for disposal at an approved landfill site.  SRIX 80097 deemed destroyed, was cleaned and dismantled.

On February 8, 2010, Veolia employees discovered a leaking 55-gallon drum while unloading a trailer truck at the Veolia TSDF facility located in Flanders, NJ. Approximately 12 gallons of material leaked onto the floor of the trailer. The leaking drum was placed into a salvage drum for disposal. The material that leaked was cleaned up with speedy dry and absorbant pads and placed into a drum for proper disposal. Upon further investigation, it was determined that the cause of the leak was because the bottom chime of the reconditioned drum had failed. The drum certification information is : UN1A2/Y1.2/100/USA/M5660/09/RL. The reconditioned drum was purchased from American Container in Rhode Island.
column169: The offeror is currently looking at alternatives to using reconditioned drums.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering ultra low sulfur diesel fuel to a customer location. While unloading the driver noticed the station did not have ulsd vapor recovery. column168: A BNSF train operating on single main track and exiting the north portal of Tunnel 9 derailed six railcars. Included in the derailment was GATX 206118 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) that derailed upright but sustained puncture or tear holes at the lower A-end tank head near the head seams. Product escaped from the compromised GATX 206118 and ignited. The ensuing fire consumed GATX 206118 and three additional loaded railcars that were positioned ahead of GATX 206118. Fires were extinguished by 1430 hrs. PST 2/21/10. Air monitoring was initiated and continued until smoldering ceased.

column62: Incorrectly Sized Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: A BNSF switch crew member reported being splashed with escaping product from the manway closure of TILX 14040 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) during normal switching operations in the railyard. The splashed BNSF employee was standing on the ground near the coupling location of TILX 14040 with another railcar. The employee immediately water rinsed impacted skin areas and was taken to a local hospital for examination and further treatment. The employee was released from the hospital with a prescription of an antibiotic burn cream and returned to duty. BNSF responders inspected TILX 14040 and reported the seal on the manway was intact. Six of eight manway securement bolt nuts were not tool tight (1 to 4 turns loose) and the other two securement bolts were not applied (hanging). The manway gasket was found to be of incorrect size and coupled with the loose closure securement prevented a good manway closure seal which allowed the product release during rail movement. BNSF contract responders fashioned a good fitting manway gasket from Gortex material and correctly positioned it in the manway lid. The manway was closed and all securement bolts were properly tool tightened. Spillage on the tank shell of TILX 14040 along with two other rail cars that were splash impacted were neutralized and cleaned. Spillage on the ground was also neutralized.  Intact seal removed was TRN 279527 and replaced with seal CHV 203417.  The side specification stencil on TILX 14040 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2007 and next due in 2017.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Reference Rayn Ayr PO No. 200916; Pilot BOL 31641 for 35 drums of Calfax 6LA70 Acid. One drum split open and spilled after leaving Pilot premises.A Pilot operator loaded the palletized drums onto a Caneda Transport box trailer approx 7:15 to 7:40 AM on Feb. 2, 2010. Chempax showed order was closed at 7:47 AM. The driver installed a bar jack and a ratchet strap to secure the freight. The driver sat in his cab until approx 8:30 AM before he drove away. He traveled I-75 North and pulled into the rest area around mile marker 28. He read and slept for approx 4.5 hours.Around 1 PM, he got out of his truck and did a trailer inspection. He noticed puddles of product at the front and rear of his trailer. He called the LCK plant stating that he would like to return to our plant to resolve the situation. The trailer arrived at the plant just after 2 PM; interviewed the driver to obtain information on the driver's company and his account of what happened. The damaged drum was at the very rear of the last row of pallets. The drum had a split about 1.5" inches in length and 2" up from the bottom of the drum. The split was along a molding seam. LCK personnel unloaded all of this freight and hosed off the bottoms of all pallets of residue. Personnel were then sent from Pilot's Middletown location to the rest area at mile marker 28 where material that had leaked from the truck was cleaned up. The driver was the one to install the load bar and the ratchet strap at the rear to secure the load. Based on the location of the ratchet bars that run along the sides of the trailer, one would expect the driver to have noticed if the drum was already split as he installed his brace and strap. Driver: Bill Savage Company: Canada Transport 4330 46th Ave. SECalgary, Alberta, Canada T2V3NT Driver had called his operation manager, Keith Meadows, in Brampton, Ontario at 403-236-7900 or 800-661-9184.
column169: Do a more thorough inspection of loaded drum trailers. Inspect with driver before he leaves.Discuss with plant personnel to not have trucks with leaking containers return to the plant but to stay where discovered in order to better address the situation.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 9, 2010, THE REGION OF NORTHERN ILLINOIS AND SOUTHERN WISCONSIN HAD BEEN EXPERIENCING A SEVERE SNOW STORM.  HENIFF TRANSPORTATION HAD A DRIVER THAT WAS HEADED WESTBOUND TO INTERSTATE 90 AT THE 166 MILE MARKER IN ROCK COUNTY NEAR EDGERTON, WISCONSIN.  THIS OCCURRED AT ABOUT 8:00PM.  THE DRIVER WAS IN THE LEFT LANE AND APPARENTLY JUST DROVE OFF THE ASPHALT PORTION OF THE LEFT SHOULDER.  WHEN THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO GET HIS VEHICLE BACK INTO THE LANE, HE MUST HAVE OVERCORRECTED.  WHEN THIS STEERING MANEUVER WAS TAKEN THE SURGE OF THE LIQUID AND THE CENTRIGUAL FORCE IN THE TANK CAUSED THE TANK TO ROLL ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE.  THE TRUCK REMAINED ON THE ROADWAY AND CAME TO REST ACROSS BOTH LANES.  THE WISCONSIN STATE PATROL HAD BEEN CALLED TO THE SCENE BY MOTORISTS DRIVING BEHIND THE HENIFF VEHICLE WHO WERE NOW UNABLE TO CONTINUE ON THE INTERSTATE.  THE MILTON TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPARTMENT ALSO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  HENIFF TRANSPORTATION RECEIVED A CALL AT ABOUT 9:00PM INFORMING US OF THE ACCIDENT.  AFTER SPEAKING TO THE DRIVER, MR. JOHN KELLY AND THE FIRE CHIEF, ROB CALHOUN ON THE SCENE, IT WAS DECIDED THAT WE NEEDED TO GET A HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM TO THE SCENE AND ALSO ANOTHER TRAILER TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT BEFORE THE ROLLED TANKED COULD BE UP RIGHTED.  A WRECKER SERVICE HAD BEEN CALLED TO THE SCENE ALSO.  THE WRECKER SERVICE HAD BEEN INSTRUCTED TO NOT ATTEMPT TO UPRIGHT THE VEHICLE UNTIL THE PRODUCT COULD BE TRANSFERRED.  I WAS INFORMED THAT THERE WAS A SMALL LEAK AND IT HAD BEEN STOPPED.  WE THEN APPROVED THEM TO DRAG THE EQUIPMENT OFF TO THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY SO TRAFFIC COULD GET BY.  THIS WAS DONE AND THE TRAFFIC WAS ALLOWED TO PASS AND THE ROADWAY WAS THEN SHUT DOWN.  HENIFF TRANSPORTATION READIED A DRIVER WITH A TRAILER AND TWO PERSONS TO ASSIST IN THE TRANSFER.  TRANS ENVIRONMENTAL HAZMAT RESPONDERS WERE PREPARING TO GO TO THE SCENE AND ASSIST HENIFF IN THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT ALSO.  TRANS ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT ABOUT 2:00AM.  THEY ATTENDED TO A SMALL DIESEL SPILL NEAR THE TRACTOR ON THE ROADWAY AND THEY WAITED FOR HENIFF TEAM TO ARRIVE. column168: A CONSOLIDATION SHIPMENT DECLARED AS NON-HAZARDOUS WAS TENDERED TO JAPAN AIRLINES CHICAGO BRANCH FROM HANKYU-HANSHIN ON FEBRUARY 9, 2010.  THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO JAPAN VIA AIR ON JL6031/10FEB.  OUR OFFICE STARTED TO GET INQUIRIES FROM OUR OFFICE IN NARITA, JAPAN ON FEBRUARY 11 ASKING IF THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED DANGEROUS GOODS.  INITIALLY THE FORWARDER THOUGHT THE SHIPMENT TO BE NON-HAZARDOUS.  OUR NARITA OFFICE THEN CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE AND THEY CONFIRMED THAT THE HOUSE AIR WAYBILL 21307827 WAS IN FACT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  WE WERE THEN SENT THE MSDS AND INVOICES FROM JAPAN.  WE MET WITH HANKYU LOCALLY AND THEY CONFIRMED THAT IT WAS A HAZARDOUS SHIPMENT.  THIS HOUSE AIR WAYBILL CONTAINED ONE SKID THAT CONTAINED MULTIPLE PIECES THAT WERE SHRINK-WRAPPED TOGETHER AND TENDERED TO THE AIRLINE AS ONE PIECE.  HAZARD LABELS OF UN1950 "LIMITED QUANTITY" AND "CONSUMER COMMODITY NOT FOR TRANSPORTATION BY AIR" WERE AFFIXED TO A BOX THAT WAS INCLUDED ON THE SHRINK-WRAPPED SKID.  THESE LABELS WERE NOT RECOGNISED AT THE TIME OF ACCEPTANCE ON FEBRUARY 9.  FROM THE PICTURES WE HAVE RECEIVED IT APPEARS THAT THE LABELS ARE FACING UP AND NOT ON THE SIDES ON THE BOX.  THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE OR DAMAGE TO THE SHIPMENT.

A FLANGE ABOVE THE BELLY VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE RAILCAR WAS NOT PROPERLY TIGHTENED.  THIS RAILCAR HAD NOT BEEN IN SERVICE SINCE IT HAD BEENN IN THE SHOP FOR REPAIRS.  THE INSPECTION REPORT SHOWS PRIOR TO GOING BACK INTO SERVICE A LEAK CHECK WAS PASSED.  THE PRODUCT LEAKED OUT FROM THE IMPROPER TIGHTENING OF THE FLANGE ABOUT THE BELLY VALVE.  PRODUCT WAS CAPTURED IN THE SPILL CONTAINMENT UNDER THE RAILCAR.  THE ESTIMATED AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LOSS WAS 350 GALLONS.  THE DURATION OF THE SPILL AND CLEANUP IS 8 HRS.  ONCE THE RAILCAR STARTED LEAKING THE CONTENTS OF THE RAILCAR WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER PRODUCT STORAGE TANK.  ONCE THE CONTENTS WERE TRANSFERRED THE LEAK BEGAN TO SLOW DOWN AND THEN EVENTUALLY STOP.
column169: THE FAILURE OF THE FLANGE WAS THE IMPROPER REINSTALLATION OF THE BELLY VALVE TO THE RAILCAR.  DISCUSSION WITH THE OUTSIDE MAINTENANCE SHOP FOUND THAT THE FLANGE WAS NOT PROPERLY TIGHTENED WHICH CAUSED A SLIGHT VOID IN AND AROUND THE FLANGE GASKET.  THIS VOID WAS ENOUGH TO HOLD A PRESSURED LEAK TEST, BUT NOT ENOUGH TO HOLD HOT LIQUID.  THE HOT LIQUID MOST LIKELY EXPANDED THE FLANGE/GASKET AND CREATED A VOID LARGE ENOUGH FOR LIQUID TO PENETRATE THE GASKET.

column168: On February 21, 2010, at approximately 8:10 a.m. CST, the driver of a tractor-trailer operated by West Texas Express lost control of the vehicle and veered off the roadway. The tractor-trailer overturned, releasing an undetermined amount of ammonia bi-chloride to the soil surface. The damaged tractor released approximately 50 gallons of diesel fuel and 1200 pounds of product to the soil surface.    On February 21, 2010,  Sentry Transportation Insurance retained Cura Emergency Services (CES) to manage the environmental cleanup operations on behalf of West Texas Express. The CES incident manager contacted Trooper Houser with Highway Patrol to gain additional information about the release. Based on available information, The CES incident manager dispatched a crew from DSC Environmental located in Ranger, Texas to assess the site and initiate corrective actions.    The crew from DSC arrived on site and met with local authorities to discuss the cleanup operations. DSC personnel secured the cap on the leaking saddle tank to prevent the further release of diesel fuel to the environment. DSC personnel then donned appropriate ppe and began to collect the containers of Haughto-Etch AX-2010 that had been released from the trailer. The top of the trailer was removed to better ventilate the work space. The DSC supervisor opened a confined space permit and DSC personnel donned respirators to enter the trailer. Upon inspection it was determined that all the containers had been damaged during the accident. The cargo was removed from the trailer and placed into roll-off containers. DSC personnel then utilized a skid steer to collect the remaining debris and impacted soil from cargo release area. Following the cleanup operations DSC personnel deconed their equipment, secured the site and de-mobilized for the day.    On February 22, 2010, DSC personnel returned to the site to complete the cleanup operations for the diesel fuel release. Guided by visual and olfactory indicators, DSC personnel utilized a backhoe to remove approximately 18 cubic yards of diesel-impacted soil from the release site. Following excavation operations, DSC personnel secured, and submitted,  four (4) confirmation soil samples for analysis by method TX1005 (total petroleum hydrocarbons). The area was then backfilled with clean fill material and re-graded to previous topography. The area was covered with TXDOT approved grass seed mixture and the crew de-mobilized.

column168: VEH #1.  VEH #1 OVERTURNED ONTO IT PASSENGER SIDE AND SLID N/B BEFORE COMING TO REST IN THE N/B LANE FACING N/E.  DR #1 WAS TRAPPED IN VEH #1 AND SUBSEQUENTLY KICKED OUT THE PASSENGER SIDE FRONT WINDOW TO EXTRICATE HIMSELF.  DEEPWATER AND MANNINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENTS ARRIVED ON SECENE.  MANNINGTON TWP. AMBULANCE SQUAD ALSO ARRIVED AND TRANSPORTED DR #1 TO THE MEMORIAL HOSPITAL OF SALEM CO. TO BE TREATED FOR AN INJURY SUSTAINED TO HIS RIGHT LEG WHICH WAS SUSTAINED WHEN DR #1 ESTRICATED HIMSELF FROM VEH #1.  VEH #1, A FUELL TANKER, HAD BEEN TRANSPORTING APPROXIMATELY 3000 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL AT THE TIME THIS ACCIDENT OCCURRED.  WHEN VEH #1 OVERTURNED, THE INTEGRITY OF THE TANK WAS COMPROMISED AND SAME LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 1000 GALLONS OF FUEL ONTO THE ROADWAY.  THE FUEL RAN OFF THE ROADWAY TRAVELING S/B AND ENTERED THE N/B AND S/B GRASS BERMS.  PERSONNEL FROM THE FIRE COMPANIES ASSISTED WITH STOPPING THE FLOW OF THE FUEL FROM THE TANKER WHILE MEMBERS OF THE SALEM COUNTY EMERGENCY SERVICES AND SALEM COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT SPREAD SAND AND DEPLOYED BOOMS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  IT WAS LATER DISCOVERED, HOWEVER, THAT THE CONTAMINATE INFILTRATED THE NEARBY KATE'S CREEK (PART OF THE MANNINGTON MEADOW).  THE REMAINING FUEL ON VEH #1 WAS OFFLOADED TO ANOTHER ROSS FOGG FUEL TRUCK THAT ARRIVED ON SCENE.  VEH #1 WAS SUBSEQUENTLY TOWED BY MARIO'S AUTO AND TRUCK REPAIR OF PEENS GROVE, NJ AND IMPOUNDED PENDING INSPECTION BY THE NEW JERSEY STATE POLICE HAZMAT TRANSPORTATION ENFORCEMENT UNIT.  OTHER AGENCIES ARRIVING ON THE SCENE TO ASSIST WERE: NEW JERSEY STATE POLICE EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT UNIT, NEW JERSEY STATE POLICE INCIDENT MANAGEMENT UNIT, NEW JERSEY STATE POLICE COMMERCIAL VEHICLE INSPECTION UNIT, NEW JERSEY DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, NEW JERSEY DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, SALEM COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT, SALEM COUNTY FIRE POLICE AND MANNINGTON TOWNSHIP EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT.  SH 45 WAS CLOSED IN BOTH DIRECTIONS FOR APPROXIMATELY 10 HOURS WHILE MONARCH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AND DAVID LAUDERETTE CO. CLEANED UP THE ROADWAY AND CONTAINED THE CONTAMINATION IN THE WATERWAY.

column168: ON SATURDAY FEBRUARY 20, 2010 THERE WAS A SPILL OF SULFURIC ACID IN THE SULFURIC TRUCK LOADING CONTAINMENT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 3:20PM.  THE TERMINAL OPERATOR WAS LOADING A SULFURIC ACID TANKER FROM THE 5000 TON STORAGE TANK WHEN THE TANKER OVERFLOWED INTO THE LOADING AREA CONTAINMENT.  THE PRODUCTION SAFETY DRIECTOR (PSD) AND SEVERAL EMPLOYEES WERE ATTENDING A HAZMAT MEETING IN THE PLANT WHEN THE WEEKEND SECURITY GUARD CAME INTO THE MEETING ROOM AT APPROXIMATELY 3:25PM TO NOTIFY THEM OF THE SPILL.  HE TOLD THEM THERE WAS A SULFURIC ACIDE SPILL IN THE TRUCK LOADING CONTAINMENT, BUT NONE HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE CONTAINMENT STRUCTURE.  THEY ARRIVED AT THE SPILL SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 3:30PM TO OBSERVE THE SPILL, WHICH HAD COVERED AN AREA APPROXIMATELY 30' BY 35' IN THE TRUCK LOADING CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SULFURIC ACID HAD FLOWED INTO THE ADJACENT ALUM STORAGE TANK CONTAINMENT AREA.  SEVERAL MEMBERS OF THE HAZMAT TEAM, ALL OF WHOM WERE ATTENDING THE HAZMAT TRAINING, SUITED UP WITH PROTECTIVE GEAR.  THE PSD HAD THE RESPONDERS START SPREADING SODA ASH ON THE SULFURIC ACID IN THE TRUCK LOADING CONTAINMENT AREA AND ON TANKER #50, FROM WHICH THE SULFURIC ACID HAD SPILLED.  THE MAINTENANCE MANAGER THEN TOOK OVER DIRECTION OF THE CLEANUP CREW.  THE PSD CONTACTED THE STATE OF MAINE PUBLIC SAFETY OFFICE AT 3:50PM AND NOTIFIED THEM OF THE SPILL AND THEY SAID THEY WOULD PASS THE INFORMATION ON TO THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION REPRESENTATIVE ON DUTY.  THE PSD THEN NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AT 3:55PM AND TALKED WITH PETTY OFFICER HUGGINS, WHO ISSUED ME REPORT #931780.  THE PSD THEN CALLED THE PRESIDENT & COO OF GAC CHEMICAL AND TALKED WITH HIS WIFE.  HE THEN CALLED THE VICE PRESIDENT OF GAC CHEMICAL AND INFORMED HER OF THE SITUATION.  THE PSD THEN RECEIVED A CALL FROM JOHN SELLECK OF THE MAINE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION (MEDEP) WHO WAS ON HIS WAY TO THE INCIDENT.  AT 4:07PM THE COO CALLED THE PSD AND WAS INFORMED OF THE SITUATION.  BY THE TIME JOHN (MEDEP) ARRIVED AT THE PLANT THE GAC HAZMAT TEAM HAD SPREAD SODE ASH OVER THE ENTIRE SPILL AREA IN THE TRUCK LOADING CONTAINMENT AND WERE SCRAPING IT UP AND PUTTING IT IN 5 GALLON POLY DRUMS.  THE HAZMAT TEAM ALSO WAS PUMPING OUT THE WEAK SULFURIC ACID FROM THE ALUM STORAGE CONTAINMENT AREA INTO TANKER #19.  THE HAZMAT TEAM ENDED UP FILLING BOTH TANKER #19 AND TANKER #35 WITH WEAK SULFURIC ACID.  THE HAZMAT TEAM ALSO WASHED OFF TANKER #50. JOHN (MEDEP) LET THE PLANT AFTER ALL THE WEK SULFURIC ACID SOLUTION HAD BEEN PUMPED OUT OF THE ALUM CONTAINMENT AREA.  SEVERAL MEMBERS OF THE HAZMAT TEAM CAME BACK INTO THE PLANT ON SUNDAY MORNING TO PUMP THE EXCESS SULFURIC ACID IN TANKER #50 INTO TANKER #49.  THEY THEN FINISHED SCRAPING UP THE SULFURIC ACID THAT HAD BEEN NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND PUT IT INTO POLY DRUMS.  IT WAS DETERMINED THE AMOUNT OF SULFURIC ACID SPILLED WAS APPROXIMATELY 695 GALLONS.  THE HAZMAT TEAM PUT 4100 GALLONS OF 13.17% SULFURIC ACID SOLUTION INTO TA

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Rollover Accident
column168: The vehicle owned and operated by Curtis Transport, Inc. was travelling Southbound on NC Highway 73. The vehicle entered a curve, and left the roadway to the right. The vehicle traveled along the unpaved shoulder, and eventually collided with a power pole and overturned. The tank trailer contained approximately 9000 gallons of E10 gasoline. NC Highway 73 was closed for approximately three hours, and nearby residential houses were evacuated for approximately four hours. The driver of the tractor-trailer was injured during the incident, and was temporarily hospitalized. There were no other injuries or fatalities.The body of the tank trailer was severely damaged during the overturn and collision incident. Approximately 7500 gallons of gasoline were released from the damaged tank trailer. The released gasoline impacted grass covered areas, a stream, and down gradient pond.Subsequent environmental remediation activities were performed, which included the recovery of petroleum product from the stream and pond, installation of containment booms and pads, and the excavation of petroleum-impacted soil. Additional environmental assessment and remediation activities are underway.
column169: Review and reinforce safe driving habits with company drivers.

column168: The driver was pumping off the product using the pump mounted on the trailer. In using his tail shaft to hook up to the pump, he was parked at such an angle when he started pumping product the tail shaft made a noise like the shaft was in a bind. So without closing any valves to stop the flow of product, the driver pulled his unit forward. When he moved his unit while still being hooked up the hose pulled away from the customer's unloading line causing product to spill on the customer's concrete pad. Only about 3/4 of a gallon spilled due to the fact that both ends,customer unloading line and trailer coupling had a dry break fitting on it. The product that was spilled was cleaned up by the customer using oil dry to absorb the product.
column169: The driver was retrained in the unloading process while pumping off product.
